dia is by no means uniform. While religion is a centerpiece of Indian nationalism, it is viewed in China as an obstacle to progress that must be marginalized and controlled. The Modern Spirit of Asia moves deftly from Kandinsky's understanding of spirituality in art to Indian yoga and Chinese qi gong, from modern theories of secularism to histories of Christian conversion, from Orientalist constructions of religion to Chinese campaigns against magic and superstition, and from Muslim Kashmir to Muslim Xinjiang. Van der Veer, an outspoken proponent of the importance of comparative studies of religion and society, eloquently makes his case in this groundbreaking examination of the spiritual and the secular in China and India.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNationalismzChinaxReligious aspects. 0aNationalismzIndiaxReligious aspects. 0aReligion and sociologyzChina. 0aReligion and sociologyzIndia. 0aSecularismzChinaxHistory. 0aSecularismzIndiaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aBangladesh.  aChen Yingning.  aChina.  aChinese Muslims.  aChinese modernity.  aChinese spirituality.  aChristian conversion.  aChristianity.  aFriedrich Max Mller.  aGandhi.  aIndia.  aIndian Muslims.  aIndian modernity.  aIndian nationalism.  aIndian spirituality.  aIslam.  aJesuit efforts.  aMughal Empire.  aMuslims.  aPakistan.  aPan-Asianism.  aSacred Books of the East.  aTagore.  aTaixu.  aWestern imperial modernity.  aWestern imperialism.  aWestern society.  aanti-imperialism.  aglobalization.  aheterodoxy.  aimperialism.  aindustrialization.  ainstitutionalized religion.  aliberalization.  aliberation.  amagic.  amaterialism.  amessianic movements.  aminoritization.  amissionary movements.  amodern vocabularies.  